The formula for the sum of neighbors depends on whether the neighbors lie in the same layer or adjacent layers.

If $n$ is in the interior of a region where all 6 neighbors are in the same layer $k$, the sum is $6n$. This happens for $n$ far from the center.

Since 2026 is in layer $k=26$, it is far from the center. The numbers in layer $k$ are bounded by $N_{k-1}$ and $N_k$. The neighbors of a number $n$ in layer $k$ (if $n$ is not near the boundaries $N_{k-1}$ or $N_k$) are expected to be in layer $k$.

The number 2026 is on the third side of layer 26, which goes from 2004 to 2029.
The neighbors of $n$ along the path are $n-1=2025$ and $n+1=2027$. Both are in layer 26.

If all 6 neighbors of 2026 are also in layer 26, then the sum is $6 \times 2026$.

Let's determine the relative position of the neighbors of $n$ on a side segment.
The side is defined by the direction vector $v$. The path moves in direction $v$.
Neighbors are $n \pm v$. The other 4 neighbors are displaced by $\pm u_i$ where $u_i$ are the other 5 unit vectors.
The sum of the 6 unit vectors is 0. If the neighbors are $n+e_i$, the sum is $6n + \sum e_i = 6n$.

For the formula to be $6n$, all 6 neighbors must exist on the grid, and we must use the standard basis vectors for the hexagonal lattice.

The only reason the sum would not be $6n$ is if one or more neighbors fall outside the spiral's defined region (i.e., they are numbers already written in a previous layer, $k-1$, or we haven't reached the next layer, $k+1$).

Since $2026$ is far from the starting number $1952$ of its layer, and far from the end number $2107$, it is highly likely that all 6 neighbors are also in layer 26.

The numbers $n$ in layer $k$ are those whose distance from the center is $k$. The neighbors of such a number will have distances $k, k-1, k+1$ from the center, depending on the direction.

If a neighbor $m$ is in layer $k-1$, then $m < N_{k-1}$. If $m$ is in layer $k+1$, then $m > N_k$.

Since $2026$ is in the middle of a long segment of layer 26, it is almost certain that all its neighbors are also in layer 26.
The segment is $2004, \dots, 2029$. $2026$ is the 23rd element.
The segment starts at $C_{1,3} = 2004$ and ends at $C_{2,3} = 2029$.
The number before $2004$ is $2003$ (end of previous segment).

The neighbors of a number $n$ on a side segment:
Let the side direction be $v$. Neighbors are $n \pm v$ (along the path).
The other 4 neighbors are: $n \pm u_1, n \pm u_2$, where $u_1, u_2$ are vectors perpendicular to $v$ (forming a 60 degree angle with $v$).

If all 6 neighbors are in the same layer $k$, the sum is $6n$.

Conclusion based on the geometric structure of a far-from-center element in a hexagonal spiral:
Since 2026 is well within layer 26 ($1952$ to $2107$), the deviation from $6n$ due to boundary effects is negligible or zero. All 6 neighbors will also be in layer 26.

$$\text{Sum of neighbors} = 6 \times 2026$$
$$6 \times 2026 = 12156$$

Final check using the structure:
If the neighbors are $n \pm e_i$, where $e_i$ are the 6 lattice vectors, then $\sum e_i = 0$, so $\sum (n+e_i) = 6n$. This is true for any point on an infinite hexagonal grid. Since 2026 is far from the edges of the spiral ($1$ and $2107$), we assume the standard lattice structure holds for its neighbors.

The sum of all 6 neighbors of the number 2026 is $6 \times 2026 = 12156$.


